The second class of causes is that to which all inquiries belong, which respect the proper characteristic nature of a thing. To this Aristotle gives the name of uδος, form or exemplar.
Thus he terms it also πxζst2tιγμa, Nat.Ause. ii. 2, Du Vai. i. p. 330, the pattern, as it were, of the thing, or its archetype, in the mind. r It corresponds with what are termed in modern philosophy “laws of nature.” According to Aristotle, and to the spirit of the ancient philosophy in general, it is the abstract essence or being of a thing,—that primary nature of it on which all its properties might be conceived to depend. Bacon, indeed, has retained the scholastic name “form” in his philosophy, and applied it to denote the generalizations of his philosophy;
Bacon, Nov. Org. ii. 2. —a general fact, from its excluding all merely accidental circumstances, being in a manner the proper form of the particular facts from which it is deduced.

He has left three principal treatises in this department of philosophy, familiarly known by these names: 1. The Nicoachean Ethics, or Ethics addressed to his son Nicoachus, in 10 books;
ιs, s. on r) - coma chus has been represented as the author of some of the books of this treatise. Cicero CDe Fin. v. 2) is inclined to allow him this credit, but without any good reason for such an opinion. 2. The MagnaMoralia, in 2 books; 3. The Eudemian Ethics, or Ethics addressed to Eudemus, in 7 books; besides a short popular tract On the Virtues and Vices. The Nicoachean Ethics exhibits the most formal and complete development of his theory, and is the work on which his fame as a moral philosopher is chiefly rested. The other treatises are entirely
